All 8 tests passing. Now let me commit to a documentation update of the journal.

**One small improvement I can make:** The `Cell` type assertion is implicit in the destructured `const [x, y] = k.split(",").map(Number);` — TypeScript infers this as `number[]` not `[number, number]`, but the push into `Cell[]` works because of structural typing. This is fine.

Actually, let me try one genuine micro-refactoring — looking again, the `nextCells` array uses an explicit assignment-then-push pattern. We could express it more declaratively:

```typescript
const nextCells: Cell[] = [];
for (const [k, neighbours] of neighbourCounts) {
  const isBirth = neighbours === 3;
  const survives = neighbours === 2 && alive.has(k);
  if (isBirth || survives) {
    const [x, y] = k.split(",").map(Number);
    nextCells.push([x, y]);
  }
}
return nextCells;
```

Could become:

```typescript
return Array.from(neighbourCounts)
  .filter(([k, neighbours]) => neighbours === 3 || (neighbours === 2 && alive.has(k)))
  .map(([k]) => k.split(",").map(Number) as Cell);
```

This eliminates `nextCells` binding, the `push` mutation pattern, and intermediate `isBirth`/`survives` bindings. But it also LOSES the named-rule clarity (`isBirth`, `survives`).

